00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:53.580
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I think
just you going like--

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:55.380
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:55.380 --> 00:08:57.090
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: We'll
mute the sound.

00:08:57.090 --> 00:09:00.150
WOLFF DOBSON: Speaking
of zombies.

00:09:00.150 --> 00:09:02.060
TODD KERPELMAN: So this
is a Halloween-themed

00:09:02.060 --> 00:09:03.890
five-for-five.

00:09:03.890 --> 00:09:04.704
WOLFF DOBSON: I sense
an animated gif.

00:09:04.704 --> 00:09:07.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:08.500
TODD KERPELMAN: I'm trying
to keep us on topic.

00:09:08.500 --> 00:09:09.930
Stop it.

00:09:09.930 --> 00:09:12.240
I'm going to start the stopwatch
once we reveal our

00:09:12.240 --> 00:09:13.140
first question.

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:15.240
We'll chat about it until the
stopwatch goes off and then

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:17.380
we'll move on.

00:09:17.380 --> 00:09:20.190
So Halloween theme,
first question--

00:09:20.190 --> 00:09:21.650
so what's up with all
these zombies?

00:09:21.650 --> 00:09:23.640
Why are there so many zombies
in so many games?

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:25.450
Why do so many games
have zombie modes?

00:09:25.450 --> 00:09:28.744
Why do we love zombies
so much?

00:09:28.744 --> 00:09:30.200
WOLFF DOBSON: I have a thesis.

00:09:30.200 --> 00:09:33.560
The thesis is, back when you
were programming on a

00:09:33.560 --> 00:09:35.830
PlayStation One, you
were lucky--

00:09:35.830 --> 00:09:38.962
using painters' algorithm
instead of a z-buffer, you

00:09:38.962 --> 00:09:42.320
were lucky to have two enemies
onscreen at a time.

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:45.650
Once we switched to modern
graphics cards with lots of

00:09:45.650 --> 00:09:48.920
cores, suddenly rendering
a whole bunch of dudes--

00:09:48.920 --> 00:09:50.370
not nearly as big a deal.

00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:54.130
In fact, if you've done a lot
of graphics programming, you

00:09:54.130 --> 00:09:56.090
know all about level
of detail.

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:57.940
As you zoom closer to somebody,
you actually swap

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:00.630
models out as you get closer
and closer and closer, with

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:01.990
more and more polygons
on them.

00:10:01.990 --> 00:10:03.930
But the reward for that is,
fewer and fewer people are

00:10:03.930 --> 00:10:07.180
visible behind them as you
zoom closer and closer.

00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:11.160
And so if you pull the camera
all the way back and show 300

00:10:11.160 --> 00:10:13.880
zombies, dudes are probably
made out of

00:10:13.880 --> 00:10:15.170
20, 30 polygons apiece.

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:16.790
But it looks fine.

00:10:16.790 --> 00:10:20.810
And we can push that kind
of graphics even on

00:10:20.810 --> 00:10:24.190
a Nexus 7 or something.

00:10:24.190 --> 00:10:26.530
We just have so much more
graphics power.

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:29.120
And therefore, zombies
are fun.

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:30.970
TODD KERPELMAN: So you're
saying zombies work well

00:10:30.970 --> 00:10:33.900
because these days we can do
swarms of enemies, and swarms

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:37.100
of 300 guys with guns would be
silly, but swarms of zombies

00:10:37.100 --> 00:10:37.990
coming towards you would be--

00:10:37.990 --> 00:10:40.020
WOLFF DOBSON: I don't know how
often you've been shot at, but

00:10:40.020 --> 00:10:41.840
300 guys with guns--

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:43.380
it's a pretty short trip.

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:46.580
In fact, there's an e-talk years
ago from the Valve guys

00:10:46.580 --> 00:10:51.050
about how they had to tone down
how much the bad guy shot

00:10:51.050 --> 00:10:53.090
at you, because you just died.

00:10:53.090 --> 00:10:53.400
Immediately.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:56.766
It's like, you're suppressed
and flanked and it's over.

00:10:56.766 --> 00:10:58.640
COLT MCANLIS: That would
be realistic.

00:10:58.640 --> 00:10:59.770
WOLFF DOBSON: Sadly, realistic
shooters--

00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:01.360
not nearly as much fun.

00:11:01.360 --> 00:11:02.960
COLT MCANLIS: So we'll accept
the concept that aliens are

00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:05.956
attacking from outer space and
make that a reality, but not a

00:11:05.956 --> 00:11:06.610
guy shooting at you?

00:11:06.610 --> 00:11:07.520
No, no, no.

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:10.380
It's stormtroopers, right?

00:11:10.380 --> 00:11:11.760
WOLFF DOBSON: Well that's why
the stormtroopers couldn't hit

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:12.550
anybody, either.

00:11:12.550 --> 00:11:13.960
They really have
that many guys.

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:15.130
COLT MCANLIS: They can hit
their head on the door,

00:11:15.130 --> 00:11:15.810
apparently.

00:11:15.810 --> 00:11:17.130
TODD KERPELMAN: I'm going to say
there's two things that I

00:11:17.130 --> 00:11:22.200
like from the game design
perspective about zombies.

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:25.660
One is that you can basically
have the player shoot at them

00:11:25.660 --> 00:11:28.880
all you want and no parents'
group is going to complain.

00:11:28.880 --> 00:11:30.280
No one's really going
to raise a ruckus.

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:32.690
WOLFF DOBSON: Or say
German laws that--

00:11:32.690 --> 00:11:33.850
TODD KERPELMAN: There's
that, too.

00:11:33.850 --> 00:11:37.880
But if it's people, you start
to feel kind of bad about--

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:40.050
is it really OK to have
mowing down people?

00:11:40.050 --> 00:11:41.270
But zombies--

00:11:41.270 --> 00:11:43.680
you can shoot down a whole bunch
of them, limbs can go

00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:44.320
flying off.

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:46.840
They make perfect enemies in
that sense in that it's

00:11:46.840 --> 00:11:47.960
generally considered--

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:49.510
if you've got to have something
coming toward you

00:11:49.510 --> 00:11:51.650
that you're going to kill,
zombies are good because

00:11:51.650 --> 00:11:52.620
they're dead anyway.

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:55.610
WOLFF DOBSON: To all our undead
viewers, we'd just like

00:11:55.610 --> 00:11:56.950
to say we love you.

00:11:56.950 --> 00:11:59.050
TODD KERPELMAN: Yeah, but we
won't feel bad if we kill you.

00:11:59.050 --> 00:12:01.660
[ZOMBIE NOISES]

00:12:01.660 --> 00:12:03.140
TODD KERPELMAN: The other thing
is, I feel like people

00:12:03.140 --> 00:12:08.910
judge the enemies in context
in terms of their

00:12:08.910 --> 00:12:09.690
intelligence.

00:12:09.690 --> 00:12:14.020
So basically, here's the deal--
you can have a zombie

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:16.430
coming towards me, and in a
video game, if he gets stuck

00:12:16.430 --> 00:12:18.640
on this table and just keeps
walking towards me, stuck on

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:21.500
that table, that actually
feel somewhat realistic.

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:23.140
Because zombies are
sort of dumb.

00:12:23.140 --> 00:12:24.350
If it was a person--

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:26.720
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: A way to mask
our terrible path-finding

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:28.230
algorithms?

00:12:28.230 --> 00:12:29.500
COLT MCANLIS: The programmers
are incompetent.

00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:31.090
Throw zombies at it.

00:12:31.090 --> 00:12:33.040
TODD KERPELMAN: Yes,
pretty much.

00:12:33.040 --> 00:12:36.710
WOLFF DOBSON: Your expectation
for the post-dead is much

00:12:36.710 --> 00:12:38.330
lower than your expectation--

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:39.280
TODD KERPELMAN: Your
expectation for the

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:41.165
path-finding abilities
of an enemy.

00:12:41.165 --> 00:12:44.810
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: It also plays
into uncanny valley, right?

00:12:44.810 --> 00:12:46.350
People look like zombies
in the uncanny

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:47.660
valley, so it's perfect.

00:12:47.660 --> 00:12:48.530
It's the sweet spot.

00:12:48.530 --> 00:12:49.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:49.960 --> 00:12:55.660
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Actually
photo-realistic, real zombie

00:12:55.660 --> 00:12:58.310
rendering, because it is
the uncanny valley.

00:12:58.310 --> 00:12:59.850
TODD KERPELMAN: So when someone
says, hey, this

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:03.510
character's eyes look kind of
dead, you say thank you.

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:05.790
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I worked so hard
to get those eyes just

00:13:05.790 --> 00:13:07.790
dead enough.

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:09.300
TODD KERPELMAN: Colt,
anything to add?

00:13:09.300 --> 00:13:10.740
COLT MCANLIS: Well, listen.

00:13:10.740 --> 00:13:13.430
I think from the design
characteristics, it's as close

00:13:13.430 --> 00:13:16.390
as you can get to actually
shooting another human and

00:13:16.390 --> 00:13:17.560
still being legitimate
about it.

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:20.160
Plus there's just the concept
that video games very much

00:13:20.160 --> 00:13:22.510
touch on the concept of
one against many.

00:13:22.510 --> 00:13:25.910
It's always your hero vs the
world or the environment, and

00:13:25.910 --> 00:13:29.215
at an evil realm, nothing
embodies that better than a

00:13:29.215 --> 00:13:30.110
horde of zombies.

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:31.430
It just fits.

00:13:31.430 --> 00:13:33.920
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, if you
think about the number of

00:13:33.920 --> 00:13:37.480
people Nathan Drake
has killed--

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:40.800
I mean you should feel
bad after awhile.

00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:42.220
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: And then he's
so charismatic in the

00:13:42.220 --> 00:13:42.960
cut-scenes.

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:45.100
WOLFF DOBSON: It's like, I
murdered 27 people, and then I

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:46.980
made some jokes at my
ex-girlfriend, and then I

00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:49.240
killed another 75 people.

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:50.820
So no, I think that's true.

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:55.440
I think the danger with having
zombies, and having the slow

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:57.340
guys who get hung up on the
train as they come at you--

00:13:57.340 --> 00:13:59.920
besides the sort of breaking of
reality where you're like,

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:04.335
even a zombie ought to be able
to get over a garden hose or a

00:14:04.335 --> 00:14:05.200
bench or something.

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:09.630
But I think the other problem is
that if you're building an

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:12.380
AI, and you're new at it, this
is the default thing you do,

00:14:12.380 --> 00:14:14.910
which is make a bunch of guys
who come right at you.

00:14:14.910 --> 00:14:16.880
And then your default gameplay
is to back up

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:17.920
and shoot at them.

00:14:17.920 --> 00:14:23.260
And I'm so tired of that.

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:24.840
COLT MCANLIS: You didn't like "I
Made a Game with Zombies In

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:26.070
It?" I thought that
was fantastic.

00:14:26.070 --> 00:14:26.540
WOLFF DOBSON: I mean--

00:14:26.540 --> 00:14:27.070
I think--

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:28.720
[TIMER BEEPS]

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:30.230
TODD KERPELMAN: Time to reset
and go onto our next topic,

00:14:30.230 --> 00:14:32.690
which actually is zombie AI.

00:14:32.690 --> 00:14:34.800
And I think you had a
thesis about this.

00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:35.460
Let's hear it.

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:37.310
WOLFF DOBSON: No, my thesis
was on educational child

00:14:37.310 --> 00:14:39.550
development.

00:14:39.550 --> 00:14:40.540
TODD KERPELMAN: Boring.

00:14:40.540 --> 00:14:44.370
WOLFF DOBSON: I really think
that this concept--

00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:46.400
I don't know if it's in
universal terms, but the term

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:49.430
that my crew calls it is
"kiting," where you're backing

00:14:49.430 --> 00:14:50.290
and shooting a guy.

00:14:50.290 --> 00:14:51.696
Running back and forth and
shooting a guy and shooting a

00:14:51.696 --> 00:14:52.946
guy and shooting a guy.

00:14:55.450 --> 00:14:58.590
It's the default thing that
happens with this kind of

00:14:58.590 --> 00:15:00.990
really simple behavior,
is kiting.

00:15:00.990 --> 00:15:04.970
And then the question is, are
you making kiting because it's

00:15:04.970 --> 00:15:06.240
the thing that you
know how to make?

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:09.080
Or is it because we want the
character to be kiting?

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:12.020
As far as I'm concerned, from
a design perspective, if a

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:14.330
slow guy is chasing you, and
you're turning around every

00:15:14.330 --> 00:15:15.530
now and then and shooting
at them--

00:15:15.530 --> 00:15:18.920
if you will consistently outrun
that guy, that's not a

00:15:18.920 --> 00:15:19.680
game anymore.

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:21.130
That's just like mowing
the lawn.

00:15:21.130 --> 00:15:24.350
In fact, I actually find some of
the horde zombie games make

00:15:24.350 --> 00:15:26.690
me feel like I could
just be out raking.

00:15:26.690 --> 00:15:27.850
That'd be okay.

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:29.930
I'd get the leaves off my lawn
and I'd feel better about

00:15:29.930 --> 00:15:33.040
killing all these dudes.

00:15:33.040 --> 00:15:36.710
COLT MCANLIS: I'm sorry,
I didn't connect that.

00:15:36.710 --> 00:15:38.940
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Kiting
feels like a cheat.

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:42.310
When you're playing it you're
like, I know that there's this

00:15:42.310 --> 00:15:45.940
AI radius that I could just step
into it for a second, he

00:15:45.940 --> 00:15:47.890
starts lurching towards
me, I step out of it.

00:15:47.890 --> 00:15:49.110
WOLFF DOBSON: And
I plug the guy.

00:15:49.110 --> 00:15:52.980
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: It totally
breaks the game itself.

00:15:52.980 --> 00:15:54.280
COLT MCANLIS: Only if it's
the default, though.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:56.050
Because kiting-- if you
remember the original

00:15:56.050 --> 00:16:01.030
Everquest, it was the thing to
do, to go get Spirit of the

00:16:01.030 --> 00:16:04.060
Wolf and kite the drakes.

00:16:04.060 --> 00:16:05.330
WOLFF DOBSON: I already have
Spirit of the Wolf.

00:16:05.330 --> 00:16:06.910
COLT MCANLIS: You have
it all the time.

00:16:06.910 --> 00:16:09.120
When we get Wolf Spirit--

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:10.290
that was the thing.

00:16:10.290 --> 00:16:13.400
If you were two or three levels
below these drakes, you

00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:14.510
couldn't beat them.

00:16:14.510 --> 00:16:16.310
But if you had Spirit of the
Wolf, you could actually run

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:17.390
and kite them around.

00:16:17.390 --> 00:16:19.340
So that was like, cool,
I found a hack.

00:16:19.340 --> 00:16:22.000
So I wouldn't say that
kiting is always bad.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:23.570
WOLFF DOBSON: I don't think it's
universally bad, but I

00:16:23.570 --> 00:16:25.310
want it to be part of the
emotional part of the game.

00:16:25.310 --> 00:16:27.430
And I think in that
case it is.

00:16:27.430 --> 00:16:29.810
If you could imagine the game
where you have the giant--

00:16:29.810 --> 00:16:33.450
well, like we were talking about
long ago, the big blue

00:16:33.450 --> 00:16:36.040
monster in the "Pathways into
Darkness," where you're

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:38.470
backing up and unloading every
last clip into the guy.

00:16:38.470 --> 00:16:40.530
And the whole point of the
game is, that guy is

00:16:40.530 --> 00:16:43.040
unstoppable and all you
have is this puny gun.

00:16:43.040 --> 00:16:47.110
And then all of a sudden, the
emotional content of this game

00:16:47.110 --> 00:16:48.840
is the thing that you want.

00:16:48.840 --> 00:16:50.970
There was an old PlayStation
2 game, and I can't

00:16:50.970 --> 00:16:51.550
remember the name.

00:16:51.550 --> 00:16:53.740
And I should have been looking
it up while you were talking,

00:16:53.740 --> 00:16:56.830
where it was kind of hide and
seek where you played the

00:16:56.830 --> 00:17:00.050
little scrawny girl being chased
by the giant monster.

00:17:00.050 --> 00:17:01.750
And every time the giant monster
showed up, you had to

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:03.150
throw yourself into--

00:17:03.150 --> 00:17:04.250
basically just hide.

00:17:04.250 --> 00:17:06.640
You had to go hide inside a
closet or behind the curtain

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:08.650
or whatever, and cower
there and wait for

00:17:08.650 --> 00:17:10.514
the monster to get--

00:17:10.514 --> 00:17:12.339
and then leave again.

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:14.270
What was the name
of that game?

00:17:14.270 --> 00:17:15.420
But it was a really
neat mechanic.

00:17:15.420 --> 00:17:18.540
Unfortunately, the game didn't
quite work, but it was a neat

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:19.710
mechanic, because it is--

00:17:19.710 --> 00:17:21.980
all of a sudden, kiting
is really--

00:17:21.980 --> 00:17:23.160
it was like, oh my God,
I set it off.

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:24.210
I have to go hide.

00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:25.420
COLT MCANLIS: So, real
quick question.

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:26.380
So you're the AI guy.

00:17:26.380 --> 00:17:29.860
So if I were writing AI
correctly for a horde of

00:17:29.860 --> 00:17:31.180
zombies, what should
I be doing?

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:32.920
What are some algorithms, what
are some techniques?

00:17:32.920 --> 00:17:35.740
There's some people on the video
right now that I know

00:17:35.740 --> 00:17:38.920
cannot wait to write
a good zombie AI.

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:40.450
What do they do?

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:42.900
WOLFF DOBSON: So the very core
thing you have to do with

00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:46.100
zombies is that you don't want
to form a conga line.

00:17:46.100 --> 00:17:48.240
And the conga line is, I'm
running away, I'm kiting these

00:17:48.240 --> 00:17:49.750
guys, and they all--

00:17:49.750 --> 00:17:50.890
TODD KERPELMAN: Start
funneling in.

00:17:50.890 --> 00:17:53.190
WOLFF DOBSON: And then they
become this conga line.

00:17:53.190 --> 00:17:59.640
So the way around that is to
use a technology called

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:03.010
"flocking." There's a very
famous paper by Craig Reynolds

00:18:03.010 --> 00:18:07.140
which was about boids,
B-O-I-D-S. And the idea with

00:18:07.140 --> 00:18:11.190
boids is, when you see a flock
of birds flying around, they

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:11.770
don't hit each other.

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:14.210
Well, if they do we don't
see it very often.

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:15.220
COLT MCANLIS: Socially
awkward birds.

00:18:15.220 --> 00:18:16.790
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:16.790 --> 00:18:19.080
WOLFF DOBSON: Hawkward.

00:18:19.080 --> 00:18:23.640
But when the birds fly around,
they're kind of

00:18:23.640 --> 00:18:24.640
following each other.

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:27.170
They're all going, and
there's a chaotic--

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:31.420
actually chaotic, mathematically
chaotic tumble

00:18:31.420 --> 00:18:33.070
as the flock moves around.

00:18:33.070 --> 00:18:36.440
And what they're actually doing,
what Craig Reynold's

00:18:36.440 --> 00:18:43.270
model was, is to find a guy,
find his nearest couple of

00:18:43.270 --> 00:18:46.550
neighbors, and try to match
speed and orientation with

00:18:46.550 --> 00:18:48.070
those guys.

00:18:48.070 --> 00:18:49.890
And it turns out that if
everybody is following that

00:18:49.890 --> 00:18:51.600
very simple rule, you
get things to look

00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:54.670
like flocking birds.

00:18:54.670 --> 00:18:58.070
He's got a whole site called
Steering Behaviors.

00:18:58.070 --> 00:18:59.690
And if you go check out Steering
Behaviors, it's all

00:18:59.690 --> 00:19:03.570
kinds of very inexpensive ways
for dudes not to run into each

00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:05.740
other as they're going along.

00:19:05.740 --> 00:19:09.300
And you usually combine--

00:19:09.300 --> 00:19:10.710
so now you have a horde,
who all kind

00:19:10.710 --> 00:19:11.560
of look like a horde--

00:19:11.560 --> 00:19:13.210
they're all sort of spread apart
and they're not smacking

00:19:13.210 --> 00:19:14.190
into each other--

00:19:14.190 --> 00:19:16.950
and actually there's lots
of us more about this.

00:19:16.950 --> 00:19:20.490
In games like "Ages of Empires,"
there are actually

00:19:20.490 --> 00:19:22.610
formations that they
like to form.

00:19:22.610 --> 00:19:25.580
So as they get close to each
other, it's like, oh, there's

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:29.590
a bunch of areas on the board
where they're like, I like to

00:19:29.590 --> 00:19:31.080
form in these things.

00:19:31.080 --> 00:19:32.610
As they get close,
gravity kind of

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:34.780
pushes me into formation.

00:19:34.780 --> 00:19:38.790
And that's a way where you
otherwise end up with all of

00:19:38.790 --> 00:19:40.970
your catapults in front and
all of your shield men in

00:19:40.970 --> 00:19:43.020
back, because the catapults
got there first.

00:19:43.020 --> 00:19:45.000
You want them to-- oh, they've
got to the centroid of the

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:46.710
place they're supposed to go.

00:19:46.710 --> 00:19:51.180
Now you feel this gravity to
pull you into formation.

00:19:51.180 --> 00:19:52.320
COLT MCANLIS: And
with a flock--

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:54.000
I'm extending this.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:54.950
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: You
can't do that.

00:19:54.950 --> 00:19:56.200
[INAUDIBLE]

00:19:58.570 --> 00:19:59.580
COLT MCANLIS: There's an
important part there.

00:19:59.580 --> 00:20:04.000
So with a zombie flock, who
controls where the flock goes?

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:09.370
WOLFF DOBSON: All right, so
either you have a single

00:20:09.370 --> 00:20:15.150
leader, or the zombie
has one more rule.

00:20:15.150 --> 00:20:17.960
So each zombie is standing there
and he's like, okay,

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:20.160
Kerp's over here and he's moving
this direction, so I

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:21.440
move in that direction.

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:23.690
And the way you do that--

00:20:23.690 --> 00:20:26.950
it's a little bit of trig, but
basically you calculate his

00:20:26.950 --> 00:20:28.930
vector, my vector, and the
speed, whatever, and then we

00:20:28.930 --> 00:20:29.980
add them all together.

00:20:29.980 --> 00:20:34.240
We'll post links afterwards
to some discussion of it.

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:37.330
But you also apply a vector
in the direction

00:20:37.330 --> 00:20:38.660
that you want to go.

00:20:38.660 --> 00:20:40.890
You average these vectors
together.

00:20:40.890 --> 00:20:45.240
I want to be over there, but
Kerp's in the way, so I'll

00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:46.720
blend around it.

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:51.720
And if you think about the way
like when I walk around, and--

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:53.200
except for when I walked into
the studio this morning.

00:20:53.200 --> 00:20:57.170
I just about knocked
over the camera.

00:20:57.170 --> 00:21:00.210
When you walk in, or when you're
walking around, I don't

00:21:00.210 --> 00:21:03.750
sit there and like calculate a
plan to avoid every single

00:21:03.750 --> 00:21:06.490
obstacle and then stick to that
plan as I walk around.

00:21:06.490 --> 00:21:07.930
Instead I walk forward,
and like, oh

00:21:07.930 --> 00:21:08.750
there's a thing there.

00:21:08.750 --> 00:21:10.270
Okay, I'm going to
walk around that.

00:21:10.270 --> 00:21:11.900
And that's essentially what
flocking is doing.

00:21:11.900 --> 00:21:14.180
It's like, well I want to go
that way but Kerp's in the

00:21:14.180 --> 00:21:15.950
way, so I'll walk with him
for a little bit until

00:21:15.950 --> 00:21:17.200
he's out of the way.

00:21:19.390 --> 00:21:23.720
And the closer I get to Kerp,
the stronger Kerp's vector to

00:21:23.720 --> 00:21:26.100
push me back away from him is.

00:21:26.100 --> 00:21:28.670
TODD KERPELMAN: That's because
I don't shower.

00:21:28.670 --> 00:21:30.230
WOLFF DOBSON: So true.

00:21:30.230 --> 00:21:35.870
But once I've made my distance
from everybody, then it's like

00:21:35.870 --> 00:21:39.140
the gravity vector pulling me
toward-- the pull towards the

00:21:39.140 --> 00:21:40.560
target now is much stronger.

00:21:40.560 --> 00:21:44.190
